Using Angular 22 httpResource for reactive HTTP state without manually managing loading, errors, and stale requests
Fetching data in Angular often starts simple:‚Äé
this.http.get<User>(`/api/users/${id}`)
.subscribe(user => {
this.user = user;
});Then the real requirements arrive.‚Äé
The route parameter changes.‚Äé
You need a loading indicator.‚Äé
The request fails.‚Äé
The user navigates quickly from /users/1 to /users/2.
Now you need to make sure an older response does not overwrite the newer one.‚Äé
Soon, a simple GET request becomes a small state-management problem.‚Äé
Angular 22 gives us another option.‚Äé
httpResource() is now production-ready, and for reactive reads it can remove a surprising amount of code.‚Äé
The Manual Version
Imagine a profile page where the selected user can change:‚Äé
import { Component, DestroyRef, inject, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { HttpClient, HttpErrorResponse } from '@angular/common/http';
import { takeUntilDestroyed } from '@angular/core/rxjs-interop';interface User {
id: string;
name: string;
email: string;
}
@Component({
selector: 'app-user-profile',
templateUrl: './user-profile.html'
})
export class UserProfile {
private readonly http = inject(HttpClient);
private readonly destroyRef = inject(DestroyRef);
readonly userId = signal('1');
readonly user = signal<User | null>(null);
readonly loading = signal(false);
readonly error = signal<HttpErrorResponse | null>(null);
loadUser(): void {
const id = this.userId();
this.loading.set(true);
this.error.set(null);
this.http.get<User>(`/api/users/${id}`)
.pipe(takeUntilDestroyed(this.destroyRef))
.subscribe({
next: user => {
this.user.set(user);
this.loading.set(false);
},
error: error => {
this.error.set(error);
this.loading.set(false);
},
});
}
}
This works.‚Äé
But we are manually maintaining three pieces of asynchronous state:‚Äé
user
loading
errorAnd userId is reactive while the HTTP request is not.‚Äé
Changing:‚Äé
this.userId.set('2');does not automatically reload anything.‚Äé
We still need:‚Äé
this.loadUser();That relationship exists only because we remembered to write it.‚Äé
Replace It with httpResource
With Angular 22:‚Äé
import { Component, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { httpResource } from '@angular/common/http';interface User {
id: string;
name: string;
email: string;
}
@Component({
selector: 'app-user-profile',
templateUrl: './user-profile.html',
})
export class UserProfile {
readonly userId = signal('1');
readonly userResource = httpResource<User>(() =>
`/api/users/${this.userId()}`
);
}
That is the entire request lifecycle.‚Äé
Read the value:‚Äé
this.userResource.value();Check whether it is loading:‚Äé
this.userResource.isLoading();Read an error:‚Äé
this.userResource.error();And when this changes:‚Äé
this.userId.set('2');the request automatically becomes:‚Äé
GET /api/users/2There is no explicit subscription connecting userId to the request.‚Äé
The request itself is reactive.‚Äé
Why Does This Work?
The function passed to httpResource() is reactive:‚Äé
httpResource<User>(() =>
`/api/users/${this.userId()}`
);Angular tracks the signals read while evaluating it.‚Äé
Here that dependency is:‚Äé
this.userId()When userId changes, Angular recomputes the request and starts loading the new resource.‚Äé
This makes the dependency explicit:‚Äé
userId
‚Üì
HTTP request
‚Üì
resource state
‚Üì
templateinstead of spreading that relationship across subscriptions and imperative methods.‚Äé
The Template Gets Simpler Too
A typical template can read the resource state directly:‚Äé
@if (userResource.isLoading()) {
<p>Loading user...</p>
}
@if (userResource.error()) {
<p>Could not load the user.</p>
}
@if (userResource.hasValue()) {
<article>
<h1>{{ userResource.value().name }}</h1>
<p>
{{ userResource.value().email }}
</p>
</article>
}You no longer need to maintain:‚Äé
readonly loading = signal(false);
readonly error = signal(null);Those states already belong to the asynchronous operation.‚Äé
The resource owns them.‚Äé
The More Interesting Part:‚Äé Stale Requests
Now try this:‚Äé
this.userId.set('1');
this.userId.set('2');
this.userId.set('3');Each value changes the resource request.‚Äé
When the request function changes while a previous request is still running, Angular aborts the obsolete request.‚Äé
This matters for interfaces where parameters change quickly:‚Äé
pagination
filters
route parameters
autocomplete
master-detail viewsWithout cancellation, you can create a race condition.‚Äé
Imagine:‚Äé
GET /users/1 ‚Üí 800ms
GET /users/2 ‚Üí 100msThe second request finishes first.‚Äé
Then the slower first request finishes and replaces your state with the wrong user.‚Äé
With a reactive resource, Angular manages the request lifecycle as the resource parameters change.‚Äé
Verify It Yourself
Create a slow endpoint:‚Äé
@Get(':id')
async getUser(@Param('id') id: string) {
await new Promise(resolve =>
setTimeout(resolve, 2000),
);
return {
id,
name: `User ${id}`,
email: `@example.com">user${id}@example.com`,
};
}Then add:‚Äé
nextUser(): void {
this.userId.update(
id => String(Number(id) + 1),
);
}And:‚Äé
<button (click)="nextUser()">
Next user
</button>Open:‚Äé
DevTools
‚Üí Network
‚Üí Fetch/XHRClick the button several times before the two-second requests finish.‚Äé
You will see the resource react to each new userId, while obsolete requests are cancelled as newer resource requests replace them.‚Äé
The observable behavior is easy to verify directly in the Network panel.‚Äé
You Still Have the Angular HTTP Stack
httpResource() is not a replacement HTTP implementation.‚Äé
It is built on Angular‚Äôs HttpClient.
That means existing HTTP infrastructure still applies, including interceptors.‚Äé
Your authentication interceptor:‚Äé
export const authInterceptor: HttpInterceptorFn =
(request, next) => {
const token = inject(AuthService).token();
return next(
request.clone({
setHeaders: {
Authorization: `Bearer ${token}`
},
}),
);
};still participates in requests made through httpResource.
You are changing how asynchronous HTTP state is consumed, not throwing away Angular‚Äôs HTTP pipeline.‚Äé
Do Not Replace Every HttpClient Call
This is where I would be careful.‚Äé
httpResource() is designed primarily for reactive data fetching.‚Äé
It is a very good fit for:‚Äé
GET /users/:id
GET /products?page=2
GET /search?q=angular
GET /dashboardwhere the result represents state that depends on reactive inputs.‚Äé
I would not automatically rewrite command-style operations like:‚Äé
POST /orders
DELETE /users/:id
PATCH /profileas resources.‚Äé
Those operations represent actions.‚Äé
They normally need explicit execution semantics:‚Äé
save()
delete()
checkout()A resource represents data that should exist as a function of some reactive input.‚Äé
That distinction keeps the architecture understandable.‚Äé
httpResource Is Not ‚ÄúRxJS Is Dead‚Äù
It also does not mean RxJS is obsolete.‚Äé
RxJS remains extremely useful when you are composing streams, coordinating events, handling WebSockets, building complex pipelines, or working with APIs that naturally expose Observables.‚Äé
The question is narrower.‚Äé
If all you are doing is:‚Äé
signal changes
‚Üí send GET request
‚Üí track loading
‚Üí track error
‚Üí expose response
‚Üí cancel stale requestyou should now ask whether manually building that lifecycle still gives you anything.‚Äé
In Angular 22, often it does not.‚Äé
Ending
The interesting part of httpResource() is not that it saves a few lines of subscribe() code.‚Äé
It changes where asynchronous state lives.‚Äé
Instead of manually coordinating:‚Äé
data
loading
error
subscription
cancellationthe HTTP operation becomes a reactive resource:‚Äé
readonly userResource =
httpResource<User>(() =>
`/api/users/${this.userId()}`
);Change the dependency.‚Äé
The request changes.‚Äé
The resource state changes.‚Äé
The template reacts.‚Äé
For read-heavy Angular applications moving toward Signals, that is a much cleaner boundary between HTTP and UI state.‚Äé
Before writing another subscribe() whose only job is copying an HTTP response into a Signal, check whether the request itself should be the Signal.‚Äé
